default4.1default 
defaultThe UK’s privatised railway is failing society, the economy and the environment, whilst draining taxpayer
defaults’ money into the pockets of private shareholders. Common sense and expert railway knowledge have ceded to a misguided private-must-be
default-
defaultbest ethos, leaving Britain with a fragmented dysfunctional railway system that other countries view with disbelief.
default&#xa0;
default4.2default 
defaultExcessive costs in the UK rail industry have recently been highlighted by the McNulty Review. This study criticised waste from fragmentation and complexity in our railways, but ignored the obvious solution: simplify the system. Instead, the Review propose
defaults more fragmentation. Analysts have predicted the McNulty approach would lead to older trains, higher fares, 
defaultand 
defaultfewer ser
defaultvices off-peak and at weekends. This would obviously lead to 
defaultfewer 
defaultand lower quality 
defaultservices to isolated 
defaultcommunities. Large sums of m
defaultoney would still be lost to inefficiencies 
defaultcaused by
default complex contractual agreements between dozens of companies.
default&#xa0;
default4.3default 
defaultThe costs associated with fragmentation and leakage of public money out of the railway translate into social costs. A portion of the publi
defaultc monies allocated for investment to increase the railway’s capacity and to improve services has instead been diverted to provide private profit. That money could have been spent on
default rebuilding and 
defaultstaffing 
defaultrun-down stations, and re-opening missing links to
default make the railway work better
default for isolated 
defaultcommunities. 
default&#xa0;
default4.4default 
defaultLeakage of money out of the privatised railway system has also reduced the amount that can be invested in rail improvements to stimulate economic activity and regeneration. This represents a 
defaultlost opportunity. For example, there is evidence that towns that lack good transport links to their nearest main city are falling behind economically: research by the Centre for Cities showed that poor train services were resulting in a widening ‘wealth ga
defaultp’ between such towns as Burnley and Blackburn and Manchester
default. There are sizeable towns lacking rail links which could benefit
default 
defaultfrom reopening rail lines and stations to attract economic investment and offer residents access to more work opportunities
default.
default 
defaultAc
defaultcording to the 2010, national rail transport survey, commuting accounts for 63 % of all rail journeys.
default 
defaultOpen Access
default4.5default 
defaultRecent political discourse, accompanied by an Office of Rail Regulation consultation, has called for an increase in open access operations which the RMT believes would have a devastating impact on the 
defaultrail network as a whole, but in particular by increasin
defaultg fragmentation and severely disadvantaging isolated communities. As such, 
defaultRMT is totally opposed to any increase in open access operations
default.
default4.6default 
defaultRMT is concerned that the government’s intention to increase these kind of operations will see the systematic d
defaultrain
defaulting
default of public money from the rail network increase as operators choose only to operate services on a commercial basis, with no rega
defaultrd to socially necessary routes serving isolated communities.
default4.7default 
defaultIn the past we have witnessed the withdrawal of open ac
defaultcess operations when the ownership of a franchise holding train operating company has changed, such as in the case of the 
defaultWrexham
default and 
defaultShropshire
default Railway.
default4.8default 
defaultFurthermore, 
defaultRMT has noted the registration of open access companies on lines such as the East Coa
defaultst mainline by operators who are also bidding for the franchise, clearly demonstrating that both the franchising and open access systems are open to abuse. 
default4.9default 
defaultOpen access operations are even 
defaultmore
default 
defaultun
defaultstable than the current franchising system with no oblig
defaultation being placed on the operator to provide any services above the bare minimum commercial services. Not only does this lead to a neglect of the sections of the railway connecting towns and villages to larger cities, but it can also lead to overcrowding 
defaulton intercity routes.
defaultDual focus franchises
default4.10default 
defaultIsolated communities have faced a further threat from a concept known as a dual-focus franchise.
default4.11default 
defaultThis type of franchise model is divi
defaultding the franchised routes in
defaultt
defaulto 
defaulttwo separate railways - 
defaultone economically viable and one socially necessary. 
default4.12default 
defaultRMT 
defaulthas noted proposals in re-franchising consultation papers which 
defaultwould increase
default the fragmentation and the complexity of the railway. 
default4.13default 
defaultFor example, t
defaulthe proposal to subdivide the Scottish rail
default network in terms of routes, fares, what is economically viable (profitable) and what is socially necessary (not profitable) in addition to creating entirely separate franchises for services such as the Caledonian Sleeper Services will be dis
defaultastrous for Sc
defaultotland’s railway, and in particular for isolated communities.
default4.14default 
defaultEssentially
default the dual focus concept 
defaultmeans shifting most of the responsibility for the socially necessary routes from the train operator onto the taxpayer and passenger, leaving the franchise
defaulte with the most profitable routes to exploit.
