defaultgovernment
default policy of 
defaultreducing hours or closing ticket offices in Category D &amp; E 
default(smaller) 
defaultstations, reducing platform staff and reducing on-train staff
default can be seen as 
defaultdirectly
default discriminating against more isolated communities
default4.18 defaultIt has been brought to the attention of RMT that First Great Western are now offering different ticket types, at different prices, on their website as from their ticket offices. RMT believes that this 
defaultis a deliberate attempt to undermine the important role of ticket offices and that it will have a significant impact on passengers in isolated communities who may, in some instances, rely exclusively on their  local ticket office for transport information.
default It sets a dangerous precedent for the entire industry, and RMT urges the Transport Committee to oppose this practice before it before endemic.
default defaultRail devolution
default4.18default 
defaultRMT notes that rail devolution/decentralisation has been proposed as a means of tacking tr
defaultansport issues in isolated 
defaultcommunities
default.
default4.19default 
defaultRMT welcomes the introduction of local democratic control where the intention is to genuinely increase democratic control of the network. It is on this basis that RMT campaigns for the railway to run in the 
defaultinterests of the travelling public as opposed to the interests of private profit. RMT believes that any increase in local democratic control must be appropriately resourced for it to be effective, and must be accompanied by national democratic control.
defaultRMT
default is concerned that devolution may be used as means in which to impose large scale cuts to staff and services, at arm’s length from central government in order to distract from the wider government agenda of imposing permanent austerity on Britain’s railway
default.
default The lessons of devolution 
defaultin the bus industry is that local authorities have either been forced to make cuts to bus services to enable the continuation of other public services or in a number of instances 
defaultauthorities
default have made unenforced 
defaultdecisions
default to buses in favour of road 
defaultdevelopment
default for cars.
defaultCurrent government policy of 
defaultforcing through staffing cuts and 
defaultprioritising the interest of the private sector over that of communities will deepen the transport isolation of many communities
default. Pr
defaultoposals around devolving transport powers, rather than helping these communities could herald a new wave of cuts in public transport that will disproportionately impact on 
default 
defaultgroups that already suffer isolation within communities such as the elderly, unempl
defaultoyed and disabled. 
